<div class='slide'>
    <h1>More Complicated Calculations</h1>
    <ul>
        <li>What if you want to do your calculation in several steps?</li>
        <li>You might want to store an intermediate value to use later</li>
        <li>In this case, you want to use <code>variables</code> to store a value in</li>
        <li>We're going to write a simple program, in the python interpreter, that lets us keep a running total of everything we spend in a day</li>
        <li>We can build on this as we learn more things</li>
    </ul>
    <div class='handout'>Now try to write an algorithm for the expenses calculator without looking at the next slide!</div>
</div>

<div class='slide'>
    <h1>Expenses Tracker Algorithm</h1>
    <ol>
        <li>Create a variable to store your subtotal in</li>
        <li>For each item:
            <ul>
                <li>Add the total to the subtotal</li>
                <li>Print the current subtotal</li>
            </ul></li>
       <li>Print the final total</li> 
    </ol>
    Don't worry about trying to automate the repetition - repeat the steps for each item manually
</div>

<div class='slide'>
    <h1>To be able to write your expenses tracker ...</h1>
    You need to be able to:
    <ul>
        <li>Store a value</li>
            <ul><li>Done using <code>=</code> </li>
            <li>Called the <i>assignment operator</i></li>
            <li>Setup the subtotal variable by storing 0 in it</li></ul>
        <li>Add two values together</li>
            <ul><li>Done just like normal maths, using +</li>
            <li>We can use the subtotal variable as one side of the expression instead of a value</li>
            <li>We then need to store the result of this calculation, </li></ul>
        <li>Print</li>
            <ul><li>Simply use the keyword <code>print</code> followed by what you want to print</li></ul>
    </ul>
